title: For Sale:  Remington Rolling Block Rifle, (7x57mm Mauser)
postcontent:
Remington Rolling Block Rifle, (7x57mm Mauser)

So this is what I just learned about this gun from a few folks viewing out my advertisement... "The Remington Rolling Block rifle was a breech-loading rifle produced from the mid-1860s into the early 20th century by E. Remington and Sons (later Remington Arms Company). The action was extremely strong, and could easily withstand the increased pressure of the new smokeless powders coming into use by the late 1880s.

It was made in a variety of calibers, both rimfire and centerfire, including the 12.17x42 mm rimfire, 12.17x44 mm rimfire and 12.17x44 mm rimmed centerfire Swedish and Norwegian cartridges, .43 Spanish (11.15x58mmR), .50-70, .45-70, and later in .22 caliber. Later models were produced in .30-06 Springfield, 7×57mm Mauser, and 8×50mmR Lebel.  During World War I, the British Royal Navy purchased 4,500 Rolling Block rifles in 7mm Mauser from Remington's leftover stock after production had ended, issuing them to the crews of minesweepers and Q-ships". http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Remington_Rolling_Block_rifle

This is my wife's aunt's rifle that she had in a case in her basement for the past 40+ years. Unfortunately, it's not in the best condition but I was wondering what an antique's gun broker would estimate the value. I recently took the rifle to a local gunsmith for his opinion about restoring it and he said not to waste my money. That is his opinion, but I feel there is more value in the rifle than what he stated.

postcontent:
I have to sell some toys to cover expenses...So up for sale is my New Mk15 Hydra by MGI industries. These unique AR15s have a proprietary switch barrel system that requires no tools. under the monolithic rail is a slide lock. release the lock slide it forward to expose 2 cam levers. Swing the cam levers out to 90 degrees and pull the barrel and gas tube free of the receiver. Change the bolt or simply have a new carrier/bolt set up ready, install and done. Can be achieved in seconds. 
The truly unique part of the MGI Hydra is the lower receiver. The problem with multi cal AR15s always revolves around the magazine well. 7.62x39 ar15 magazines are renowned for their unreliability, Pistol calibers for their finicky magazine blocks, and limitations of calibers by the size of the mag well. MGI fixed that in this design. The magazine well slide into and locks on machined rails in the receiver. Yes...the magazine well is removable. The magazine wells take the ammunition's native magazine. The 7.62x39 takes AK mags, 9mm takes glock mags with no block needed. Everything from .22lr to .50 beouwulf is already available. Conversion Kits can be ordered directly from MGI and come with magazine well barrel and bolt specific to the caliber and the mag well specific to magazine used. They are also the only ones offering a .308/762x51 conversion in an AR15 (not AR10 frame) by using their mag well and magazine.....why have to carry several rifles or have to keep several on hand. One AR can do it all. Saves space and carry loads.
Comes with over sized pistol case that holds upper lower and 2 barrels Plus ammo can with mags and ammo.
